  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Philemon 1:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἅμα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " … ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", at the same time that he does what he is going to do for Onesimus. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἑτοίμαζέ μοι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": Lightfoot’s remark that “there is a gentle compulsion in this mention of a personal visit to Colossae,” does not seem justified in view of the stress that St. Paul lays on Philemon’s action being wholly voluntary, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Philemon 1:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Philemon 1:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; it is more probable that this is merely an incidental mention of what had been planned some time before, namely another missionary journey to Asia Minor and Greece (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Php 2:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), without any thought of influencing Philemon’s action thereby.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ξενίαν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": only here and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 28:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in the N.T.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". He hopes to visit Colossæ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "But withal",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Here is a different matter, yet not quite apart from the main theme. “There is a gentle compulsion in this mention of a personal visit to Colossæ. The Apostle would be able to see for himself that Philemon had not disappointed his expectations” (Lightfoot). And more; would not the joy of the prospect make “obedience” on Philemon’s part doubly willing?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "prepare",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The verb is in the singular.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a lodging",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The Greek may mean either “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "lodging",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "” or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "hospitality",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". General Greek usage is in favour of the latter. The “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "hospitality",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "” would no doubt be gladly provided in Philemon’s own house; but St Paul, with his unfailing courtesy, does not ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ask",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " this.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I trust",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "I hope",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". He makes no prophecy, where none is authorized. Even when (as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 15:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 15:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") he speaks positively of his plans, it is with an evident reservation of “if the Lord will.” The prospect of Romans 15 had by this time been much modified.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "through your prayers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] which “move the hand of God,” being all the while part of His chain of means. For St Paul’s estimate of the power of intercessory prayer see e.g. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 15:30-32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (a close parallel); a Cor. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Philemon 1:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Php 1:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—Neither for him nor for the Colossians did the deep peace of self-resignation mean Stoic apathy, nor, surely, even the “indifference” of the Mystics.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I shall be given unto you",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] With a noble ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "naïveté",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " he recognizes his own dearness in the eyes of his converts; he does not affect to think that his return would not be “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a gift",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "” to them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lightfoot cites ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 25:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for the use of the Greek verb in connexion with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a person",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
