  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 22.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Lodging",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". There was this one additional inducement that could be brought to bear upon the mind of Philemon, viz. the expectation of speedily seeing him in person, and this, in conclusion, he uses. \"I do not think that the apostle was so rich or encumbered with such great packages that he needed a lodging prepared beforehand, and was not content with a narrow dwelling-place, but thought the most spacious houses scanty for the accommodation of his small body; but that, while Philemon was expecting [the apostle] to come to him, he would the more do what he had requested\" (Jerome). Meyer makes much of the improbability that St. Paul, starting from Rome, should bespeak a lodging in Colossae. Yet he suggests that it was  perfectly natural that, starting from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Caesarea",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the apostle should take ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Colossae",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " on the road to Rome. But the one seems almost as probable as the other. The apostle, on his release, had, so far as we know, no definite plans; the cities of Asia Minor were familiar to him, and he would naturally prepare to go wherever the first pressing occasion, that of Onesimus, called him. N reads ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀσπάξεται",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"salutes.\" Philemon 1:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Withal (ἅμα)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Simultaneously with the fulfillment of my request.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A lodging",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Paul is expecting a speedy liberation. His original plan of going from Rome to Spain has apparently been altered. Lightfoot observes that \"there is a gentle compulsion in this mention of a personal visit to Colossae. The apostle would thus be able to see for himself that Philemon had not disappointed his expectations.\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "I shall be given (χαρισθήσομαι)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A beautiful assumption of his correspondent's affection for him, in that his visit to them will be a gracious gift (χάρις) The word is also used of granting for destruction, Acts 25:11; or for preservation, Acts 3:14. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "A beautiful assumption of his correspondent's affection for him, in that his visit to them will be a gracious gift (χάρις) The word is also used of granting for destruction, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 25:11",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; or for preservation, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 3:14",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
]